otropic scattering and a\nscattering screen halfway between the pulsar and earth. We also estimate the\nlocation of the scattering screens assuming proper motion and interstellar\nscattering-derived transverse velocities are equal. We find no correlations\nbetween variations in scattering delay and either variations in dispersion\nmeasure or flux density. For most pulsars for which scattering delays were\nmeasurable, we find that time of arrival uncertainties for a given epoch are\nlarger than our scattering delay measurements, indicating that variable\nscattering delays are currently subdominant in our overall noise budget but are\nimportant for achieving precisions of tens of ns or less.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 17 Dec 2020 19:09:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 30 Apr 2021 20:38:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-18"}
